<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Can I use AI-generated music on YouTube without copyright claims?</h3>
<p>Yes, if you use a tool that grants you commercial ownership of the output. Suno AI (Pro plan), AIVA (all plans), and Boomy (all plans) all give you full rights to use the music on YouTube without copyright claims. Always confirm the licensing terms of your specific plan — free tiers may restrict commercial use.</p>

<h3>Which AI music generator has the most permissive license?</h3>
<p>AIVA and Boomy have the most permissive licenses because they grant full commercial ownership even on their free plans. You can create music, use it in commercial projects, and publish it on streaming platforms without paying anything. Suno AI's Pro plan is also very permissive at just $10/month.</p>

<h3>Do I need to credit the AI tool in my videos?</h3>
<p>Generally, no — most AI music generators with commercial licenses do not require attribution. However, some free tiers (like Suno's free plan) may require attribution for non-commercial use. Always check the specific terms of service for the tool you're using. When in doubt, upgrading to a paid plan almost always removes any attribution requirement.</p>

<h3>Can I sell AI-generated music?</h3>
<p>Yes, if the tool's license permits commercial use and transfer of ownership. Suno AI (Pro and Premier), AIVA (all plans), and Boomy (all plans) allow you to sell or license your AI-generated music. Some platforms may restrict this on their free tiers. Read the terms carefully — some tools retain certain rights or prohibit direct resale of unmodified AI output.</p>

<h3>What's the difference between "royalty-free" and "no copyright"?</h3>
<p>"Royalty-free" means you don't have to pay ongoing royalties or licensing fees to use the music — you pay once (or subscribe) and use it freely. "No copyright" (or public domain) means the work is not protected by copyright law and anyone can use it without restriction. Most AI music generators grant you ownership of the output (you hold the copyright), which is different from public domain — but for practical purposes, you can use it freely for commercial projects without paying additional fees.</p>

<h2>Final Verdict</h2>

<p>If you need complete songs with vocals and the best all-around quality, <strong>Suno AI's Pro plan ($10/mo)</strong> is the top choice for no-copyright AI music. It gives you full commercial ownership of professional-quality tracks across dozens of genres.</p>

<p>For orchestral, cinematic, or classical compositions, <strong>AIVA</strong> is the clear winner — and its free plan includes commercial rights, making it the most accessible option for budget-conscious creators.</p>

<p>If you want to create and release music immediately without spending anything, <strong>Boomy's free tier</strong> gives you full ownership with no restrictions, though the output quality is more basic.</p>

<p>For content creators who need background music and loops, <strong>Stable Audio's Pro plan ($11.99/mo)</strong> offers excellent instrumental quality with clean commercial licensing. And if you want maximum creative control over individual instruments, <strong>Soundraw ($19.99/mo)</strong> is a powerful hybrid option.</p>

<p>The bottom line: in 2026, there's no reason to risk copyright strikes on your content. AI music generators with no copyright restrictions make it easy, affordable, and legal to create custom music for any project.</p>


